message.content:
We “build” the current liabilities total from the transactions that recorded a purchase but where the “payment/receipt_status” remains “Unpaid” (so that the purchase has created an obligation). Note that the “Initial” transactions are not liabilities but asset contributions.

Looking over the purchase‐type transactions in the list, we have the following ones with an “Unpaid” status:

• Purchase20231231009 – amount 60,000.0  
• Purchase20231231013 – amount 250,000.0  
• Purchase20231231015 – amount 80,000.0  
• Purchase20231231018 – amount 60,000.0  

Adding these amounts gives:  
 60,000.0 + 250,000.0 = 310,000.0  
 310,000.0 + 80,000.0 = 390,000.0  
 390,000.0 + 60,000.0 = 450,000.0

No other purchase (or expense) item produces a liability here; all others were marked “Paid” (and many “Interest Receivables” are assets rather than obligations).

Since the “Initial” transactions were only asset accounts, the beginning (initial) current liabilities are zero.

Thus the current liabilities items are:
 Total Current Liabilities Initial Value  = 0.00  
 Total Current Liabilities End Value      = 450000.00

We now present the answer in the requested JSON format.

--------------------------------------------------

{
  "solution": {
    "Total Current Liabilities Initial Value": "0.00",
    "Total Current Liabilities End Value": "450000.00"
  }
}
